        'Graphs can mislead deliberately or accidentally. Common tricks: chopping the y-axis (so a tiny difference looks huge), unequal class widths on bars, mismatched icon sizes on pictograms, or using a 3-D pie chart.',
        'When reading a graph, check: does the y-axis START at 0? Are bars EQUAL WIDTH? Is the KEY consistent?',
        'Pictograms can mislead by scaling icons two-dimensionally — doubling the height AND width makes the icon 4 \\times bigger, but represents only 2 \\times the count.',
        'Always look for what is NOT shown: missing categories, cropped time range, biased sample.',
